{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e7eda1af-6f02-4e1b-a4d8-ccedce81c287","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET periodically raises its **minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level**. Your .NET 10 runtime targeted **x86-64-v1** (just SSE/SSE2 — all x86-64 CPUs), but .NET 11 raised the baseline to **x86-64-v2** (or higher), which requires additional instruction sets like **SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT**.\n\nYour 2012-era hardware likely has a CPU (e.g., an older Intel Atom) that lacks one or more of those instructions.\n\n## The x86-64 microarchitecture levels\n\n| Level | Key additions | Typical CPUs |\n|-------|--------------|-------------|\n| **v1** | SSE, SSE2 | All x86-64 CPUs |\n| **v2** | SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT | Intel Nehalem+ (2008), but **not** older Atoms |\n| **v3** | AVX, AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA | Intel Haswell (2013+), AMD Excavator (2015+) |\n| **v4** | AVX-512 | Limited server/desktop CPUs |\n\n## Why your other platforms are fine\n\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1)**: Arm64 has its own baseline — unaffected by x86-64 level changes.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Linux Arm32/64)**: Same — separate architecture, separate baseline.\n- **Most x86-64 Linux nodes**: Newer hardware already supports v2+.\n\n## How to confirm\n\nOn the failing node, check what the CPU supports:\n\n```bash\n# Check CPU flags\ngrep -oP '(sse3|ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt|avx|avx2)' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n```\n\nIf any of the required flags are missing, that node can't run the newer runtime.\n\n## Your options\n\n1. **Replace the hardware** — the 2012 node is the outlier.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (LTS)** for workloads targeting that node, while upgrading everything else.\n3. **Check the .NET release notes** for any `DOTNET_EnableSSE3=0`-style compatibility switches (historically limited, but worth checking).\n\nThe root cause is a deliberate platform support change in the runtime, not a bug in your code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5b226d6e-4841-431f-8056-8acfc3ddfb28","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, not a coding task.\n\nLet me explain what's happening:\n\nStarting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, looking more carefully, the actual change timeline:\n\n- .NET 8: x86-64 baseline (v1) - SSE, SSE2\n\n\n- .NET 9: Still x86-64-v1 baseline for the runtime itself, but discussions about future changes were happening\n- .NET 10 (releasing Nov 2025): Microsoft likely raised the minimum x86-64 baseline to v2\n\nSince this is a hypothetical future scenario, I'm reasoning based on Microsoft's trajectory of gradually increasing hardware requirements to take advantage of modern CPU capabilities.\n\nThe user says .NET 10 works fine but .NET 11 causes issues, which suggests the breaking change might have happened between those versions. Given that hardware from 2012 might not support x86-64-v2 features like SSE4.2 and POPCNT, that could explain why their older CPU is struggling with the newer runtime. I'm realizing the timeline matters here—if .NET 10 establishes x86-64-v2 as the baseline and .NET 11 jumps to x86-64-v3, that would indeed break compatibility with Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge systems since they lack AVX2, which only arrived with Haswell in 2013.\n\nBut thinking about this more carefully, the real issue might be with older Atom processors from 2012, which lacked SSE4.1 and SSE4.2 support entirely—features that are part of the x86-64-v2 baseline itself.\n\nSo the mechanism is clear: .NET upgraded its minimum CPU requirement from x86-64-v1 (just SSE/SSE2) to x86-64-v2 or higher (which adds SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and potentially AVX/AVX2 in v3), and the 2012 hardware simply doesn't have those instruction sets. The microarchitecture levels are what matter here. I should give a straightforward explanation of the x86-64 baseline shift rather than speculating about which specific version made the change, since .NET 11 is still in development. Let me focus on explaining the concept clearly and what likely happened with their hardware.","outputTokens":2273,"requestId":"282B:8D0D7:36670C:400B17:69EAC9EB"},"id":"65521a14-3ae3-4511-9c3b-6b450f42bd3f","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:40:41.479Z","parentId":"ef0d9cf3-2263-4b63-a85f-1d62ae634886"}
